"title": "6206: offence",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "6206",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>A transgression or affront against the law or an individual. The gospel itself is seen as offensive by unbelievers, who are often unable to cope with its radical challenge to their unbelief.</p>\n<h2>Legal offence</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut21:22-Deut21:23\">DEU 21:22–21:23</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod21:15-Exod21:25\">EXO 21:15–21:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod22:1-Exod22:5\">EXO 22:1–22:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut19:15-Deut19:21\">DEU 19:15–19:21</a></p>\n<h2>Moral offence</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek22:11\">EZK 22:11</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod22:16-Exod22:17\">EXO 22:16–22:17</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev18:6-Lev18:23\">LEV 18:6–18:23</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut22:13-Deut22:30\">DEU 22:13–22:30</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam3:8\">2SA 3:8</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor6:9-1Cor6:10\">1CO 6:9–6:10</a></p>\n<h2>An offence to others</h2>\n<h3>On a national level</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam13:4\">1SA 13:4</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam10:6\">2SA 10:6</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr19:6\">1CH 19:6</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer24:9\">JER 24:9</a></p>\n<h3>On a personal level</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam16:21\">2SA 16:21</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen20:1-Gen20:16\">GEN 20:1–20:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen40:1\">GEN 40:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam25:14-1Sam25:28\">1SA 25:14–25:28</a> <em>Abigail seeks David's forgiveness for Nabal's offence</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job19:17\">JOB 19:17</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov17:9\">PRO 17:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov18:19\">PRO 18:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov19:11\">PRO 19:11</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt13:54-Matt13:57\">MAT 13:54–13:57</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark6:1-Mark6:4\">MRK 6:1–6:4</a> <em>The people of Nazareth take offence at Jesus Christ</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt15:1-Matt15:12\">MAT 15:1–15:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt17:24-Matt17:27\">MAT 17:24–17:27</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John6:53-John6:66\">JHN 6:53–6:66</a></p>\n<h2>Offence against God</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs8:50-1Kgs8:51\">1KI 8:50–8:51</a></strong> <em>Offence against God is synonymous with sin.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job7:21\">JOB 7:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job10:14\">JOB 10:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job13:23\">JOB 13:23</a> <em>“wrongs”, “sins” and “offence” are three important OT terms for sin</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job14:16-Job14:17\">JOB 14:16–14:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job34:31-Job34:33\">JOB 34:31–34:33</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps59:3\">PSA 59:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps139:24\">PSA 139:24</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa43:24\">ISA 43:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa44:22\">ISA 44:22</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa59:12\">ISA 59:12</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek18:1-Ezek18:32\">EZK 18:1–18:32</a> <em>Ezekiel warns that the soul who sins will die</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek33:10\">EZK 33:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek37:23\">EZK 37:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek39:24\">EZK 39:24</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos5:12\">AMO 5:12</a></p>\n<h2>Offence against God's house</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num18:1\">NUM 18:1</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num18:23\">NUM 18:23</a></p>\n<h2>The things of God are an offence to sinful people</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer6:10\">JER 6:10</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor1:22-1Cor1:24\">1CO 1:22–1:24</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal5:11\">GAL 5:11</a></p>\n<h2>A stumbling-block as an object of offence</h2>\n<h3>A stumbling-block for others</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom14:13\">ROM 14:13</a></strong> <em>The concept behind the English word “offence” is one of striking against something or someone. The image of a stumbling-block conveys the idea of tripping or falling as a result of striking against such an object.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev19:14\">LEV 19:14</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt16:23\">MAT 16:23</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom11:9-Rom11:10\">ROM 11:9–11:10</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps69:22-Ps69:23\">PSA 69:22–69:23</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor8:9\">1CO 8:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor6:3\">2CO 6:3</a></p>\n<h3>A stumbling-block for oneself</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek14:7\">EZK 14:7</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek14:3-Ezek14:4\">EZK 14:3–14:4</a></p>\n<h3>A stumbling-block set up by God</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek3:20\">EZK 3:20</a></strong></p>",
